### G) kAIxU Smoke Timeline: The Full Failure -> Patch -> Pass Story
1. Built a dedicated heavyweight browser smoke at `scripts/smoke-kaixu-platform-playwright.mjs` and added `npm run smoke:kaixu-platform` in `package.json`.
2. The smoke checks both direct surface loads and shell embedding for the kAIxU platform page, suite page, and the individual app family.
3. The target was not cosmetic. The target was to prove the family actually mounts, identifies itself correctly, and survives real navigation in the runtime.
4. First smoke attempt failed before the suite was even tested because Playwright browser binaries were missing.
5. Patched by installing the required Playwright browser package.
6. Second smoke attempt failed before browser execution because the Linux runtime dependencies required by Playwright/Chromium were missing in the container.
7. Patched by installing the missing Linux shared library dependencies.
8. Third smoke attempt finally ran real browser checks and exposed the first true reliability wave.
9. Failures at that stage were a mix of:
10. preview/service-worker noise creating false negatives
11. over-strict structural expectations in the smoke itself
12. real shared-frame boot timing risk in the kAIxU product-positioning bridge
13. Patched the shared kAIxU frame bootstrap so it no longer assumes body/nav markup already exists before execution.
14. Patched the smoke expectations so preview-only service-worker registration noise would not be mistaken for app failure.
15. Patched the smoke to use per-surface structural requirements instead of forcing every kAIxU surface into the exact same mount assumptions.
16. Fourth smoke attempt improved sharply and collapsed the failure list down to one remaining real offender: `kAixu-Nexus`.
17. Root cause there was structural drift caused by the Vue-driven layout/mount behavior. The generic injected frame assumptions were not reliable enough for Nexus.
18. Patched `public/kAixu-Nexus/index.html` with explicit runtime anchors, including a native `#kaixu-platform-frame` ribbon and a stable navbar identifier.
19. Final smoke run passed clean.
20. Verified result: `surfaces=16`, `checks=32`, `failed=0`.
21. Artifact emitted at `artifacts/kaixu-platform-smoke.json`.
22. Bottom line: the smoke did exactly what it was supposed to do. It found real bootstrap risk, one structural outlier, a bunch of false-negative assumptions, and forced the kAIxU family into a genuinely reliable shipped state instead of a hand-wavy “looks good” state.

